<p>
This site demonstrates <a href="https://github.com/philhawksworth/netlify-plugin-fetch-feeds">netlify-plugin-fetch-feeds</a>, a <a href="https://docs.netlify.com/configure-builds/build-plugins/?{{ site.utm }}">Build plugin</a> for <a href="https://netlify.com?{{ site.utm }}">Netlify</a>
</p>
<p>
  Code for this demo site in available in on <a href="{{ pkg.repository.url }}">GitHub</a>.
</p>
<p>
  When this example site is generated, the build plugin requests (and caches for future builds) these feeds:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><a href="https://www.netlify.com/blog/index.xml?{{ site.utm }}">https://www.netlify.com/blog/index.xml</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://hawksworx.com/feed.json">https://hawksworx.com/feed.json</a></li>
</ul>
<p>
  The data feeds and the duration of their caching can be configured in <a href="{{ pkg.repository.url }}blob/master/netlify.toml">the netlify.toml</a> config file. Once requested, the data is available for the site generator to use as below.
</p>

<h2>Netlify blog</h2>
